      <hedline>
        <hl1>About Men, Women and Abortion</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott A Rothstein letter says Thomas Lynch's suggestion that allowing a man freedom to disclaim his responsibilities for fathering a child while woman is still pregnant misses point that once choice is made to give birth, concern shifts from equalizing rights of parents to welfare of baby (July 5 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Man's Right to Choose'' (Op-Ed, July 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Man's Right to Choose'' (Op-Ed, July 5):</p>
        <p>Thomas Lynch suggests that allowing a man the freedom to disclaim his responsibilities for fathering a child while the woman is still pregnant will help equalize the rights between the man and the woman.</p>
        <p>Mr. Lynch misunderstands the issue. Perhaps it is inequitable that the decision to give birth is, practically speaking, ultimately the woman's to make. But once a choice has been made, the concern shifts from the parents' rights to the welfare of the baby, who, after all, had the least opportunity for decision-making.</p>
        <p>SCOTT A. ROTHSTEIN  Massapequa, N.Y., July 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
